    <h1>Limits and Colimits</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Bartosz Milewski · 2015 · <a href="https://bartoszmilewski.com/2015/04/15/limits-and-colimits/">Category Theory for Programmers, Ch. 11</a></p>

    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">Prereqs: <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-05/">🍞 Ch5</a> (Products and Coproducts), <a href="/reading/category-theory/milewski-10/">🍞 Ch10</a> (Natural Transformations). 10 min.</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>limit</strong> is a universal cone over a diagram. Products, terminal objects, and equalizers are all limits. Reverse the arrows and you get <strong>colimits</strong>: coproducts, initial objects, and coequalizers. One construction, many shapes.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Diagrams and cones -->
    <h3>Diagrams and cones</h3>
    <p>A <strong>diagram</strong> is a functor D : I → C from an index category I (the "shape") into a target category C. A <strong>cone</strong> over that diagram is an apex object <em>c</em> together with morphisms from <em>c</em> to every object in the diagram, such that every triangle commutes. Think of a tent pole (<em>c</em>) with ropes (morphisms) to each stake (diagram object), where every rope follows the connections between stakes.</p>

